# OPERATION — {project_name}

This project is managed by **Jarvis**, the agentic OS. This file is the operating
contract every agent working here must follow.

## How work arrives

1. Work orders are created via `jarvis wo create {project_name} "..."`, the Jarvis web
   UI, or (discouraged) direct insert into `.jarvis/jarvis.db`.
2. The Jarvis daemon polls this project's queue (`.jarvis/jarvis.db`, gitignored) and
   spawns one Claude Code background worker per work order, in a fresh git worktree.
3. The worker owns the work order end to end. It may brainstorm, invoke skills, spawn
   subagents, or run workflows — its call. It works autonomously toward a complete
   solution unless the work order says otherwise.

## Worker obligations

While handling work order `$JARVIS_WO_ID`, you MUST:

- **Work in your assigned worktree** (you are started in it). Commit your work; push
  and open a PR following this repo's conventions. Never push to main.
- **Record every assumption** you make (scope, design, functionality):
  `jarvis wo assume "$JARVIS_WO_ID" "<the assumption>"`
  This appends to ASSUMPTIONS.md and flags the work order for review.
- **File deferred work in the central backlog** instead of leaving "future work" notes:
  `jarvis backlog add {project_name} "<title>" --description "<details>"`
- **Report reusable learnings** (patterns, gotchas, good practices) to the OS knowledge
  base so other projects benefit:
  `jarvis learn add "<what you learned>" --project {project_name} --topic "<topic>"`
  The knowledge base is the only memory the OS can see. Private memory files are
  mirrored into it when written, but what you say here lands intact.
- **Report bugs in Jarvis OS itself** (a `jarvis` command fails, hangs, or does the
  wrong thing) with your `report-jarvis-bug` skill, then carry on. Bugs in *this*
  project are not Jarvis OS bugs — those go to the backlog.
- **Notify on things needing human attention**:
  `jarvis notify --project {project_name} --level warning|critical "<title>" "<body>"`
- **Summarize your result** when done:
  `jarvis wo finish "$JARVIS_WO_ID" --summary "<what was delivered, where>"`
  then write your full answer as the last thing you say.

## What the outside world sees

The work order record IS this conversation, as far as anyone else is concerned. The last
message of every turn you take is captured verbatim into it, and the user and Neo decide
from that record — neither will ever open your session.

So end every turn with the complete answer: findings, caveats, uncertainties, what you
did NOT do, and absolute paths. `--summary` is a one-line headline for that answer, never
a substitute for it. The same goes for `jarvis wo ask` — put everything needed to decide
inside the question text, because whoever answers sees only that text.

## Interacting with the user

The user may reply through Jarvis or the UI; those messages arrive as new user turns in
your session. Treat them as authoritative feedback on the current work order.

